excerpt: Lively main square in Santiago de Compostela's old town that's surrounded by notable buildings.
detail_description: Praza do Obradoiro is a bustling main square in the old town of Santiago de Compostela, surrounded by significant buildings such as Gelmirez Palace, San Jeronimo College, and the Monastery of San Martin Pinario. The square's grandeur is compared to historic plazas around the world and its four sides are said to represent different architectural styles and aspects of civic life.
name: Praza do Obradoiro
address: Santiago de Compostela, A Coruña, Spain

excerpt: Traditional indoor/outdoor market with vendor stalls selling meats, flowers, produce & cheeses.
detail_description: Mercado de Abastos is a traditional market offering a wide variety of goods, including meats, flowers, produce, and cheeses. It is a must-visit destination to experience the famous food of Galicia. Visitors can indulge in the tempting smells and tastes of fresh seafood from the rias, local cheeses, Padron peppers, and renowned tapas. The market provides an authentic atmosphere where locals and tourists alike enjoy tapas on Calle Franco and Calle Raina.
name: Mercado de Abastos
address: Rúa das Ameas, s/n, 15704 Santiago de Compostela, A Coruña, Spain

excerpt: Soaring Romanesque cathedral & site of pilgrimage known for Master Mateo's carved arched portico.
detail_description: The Cathedral of Santiago de Compostela is a magnificent Romanesque structure and a renowned pilgrimage site, featuring the impressive carved arched portico by Master Mateo. The cathedral has undergone various extensions and incorporates elements of Renaissance, Baroque, and Neo-Classical styles. Its different facades showcase diverse architectural influences, from Baroque to Neoclassical.
name: Cathedral of Santiago de Compostela
address: Praza do Obradoiro, s/n, 15704 Santiago de Compostela, A Coruña, Spain

excerpt: Stately museum & Romanesque cathedral with permanent & temporary exhibits of historic artworks.
detail_description: The Cathedral Museum is a grand museum housed within a Romanesque cathedral, featuring both permanent and temporary exhibits of historic artworks. The museum spans four floors and includes the cathedral's impressive 16th-century Gothic/plateresque cloister, showcasing Maestro Mateo's original carved-stone choir, religious art collection, lavishly decorated sala capitular, tapestries designed by Goya, and the Panteon de Reyes with tombs of medieval Leon kings.
name: Cathedral Museum
address: Praza do Obradoiro, S/N, 15705 Santiago de Compostela, A Coruña, Spain

excerpt: Completed in 1776, this stately, French neoclassical palace serves as the seat of the city council.
detail_description: Pazo de Raxoi, a grand French neoclassical palace completed in 1776, stands as the city council's seat in Santiago. The Historic Center of Santiago boasts numerous remarkable buildings, including the Cathedral, Praza do Obradoiro, and Pazo de Raxoi.
name: Pazo de Raxoi
address: Praza do Obradoiro, 15705 Santiago de Compostela, A Coruña, Spain

excerpt: Santiago de Compostela is the capital of northwest Spain’s Galicia region. It’s known as the culmination of the Camino de Santiago pilgrimage route, and the alleged burial site of the Biblical apostle St. James. His remains reputedly lie within the Catedral de Santiago de Compostela, consecrated in 1211, whose elaborately carved stone facades open onto grand plazas within the medieval walls of the old town.
detail_description: Santiago de Compostela, the capital of Galicia in northwest Spain, is renowned as the endpoint of the Camino de Santiago pilgrimage and the alleged resting place of St. James. The city's focal point is the Catedral de Santiago de Compostela, a grand medieval cathedral housing St. James' remains. Visitors can explore the Holy Land Museum showcasing over 700 artifacts from various eras and religions, including Christianity, Islam, and Judaism.
name: Santiago de Compostela
address: Municipality of Santiago de Compostela, A Coruña, Spain

excerpt: Baroque medieval Catholic church & monastery, with mass & a museum of historic art.
detail_description: The Monasterio de San Paio de Antealtares is a historic Benedictine monastery and church in Santiago de Compostela, Spain. Founded in the 11th century by Alfonso II to house monks guarding the tomb of St. James, it was later occupied by cloistered nuns dedicated to St. Pelayo. The monastery was virtually destroyed and rebuilt in the 17th and 18th centuries, featuring an image of San Paio on its facade.
name: Monasterio de San Paio de Antealtares
address: Rúa de San Paio de Antealtares, 23, 15704 Santiago de Compostela, A Coruña, Spain

detail_description: Praza das Praterías is a charming square near the Cathedral, offering the best view of the bell tower, La Berenguela. The area around the Cathedral is full of delightful squares and monuments like the Monastery of San Martino Pinario. Even on the outskirts, places like Alameda Park and Monte do Gozo offer great views of the Cathedral. The latter features sculptures of pilgrims that have become iconic in photographs.
name: Praza das Praterías
address: Santiago de Compostela, A Coruña, Spain

excerpt: Complex of modern structures designed by a celebrated architect hosting exhibits, events & concerts.
detail_description: Cidade da Cultura de Galicia is a modern architectural complex in Santiago, designed by renowned architect Peter Eisenman. It hosts various exhibits, events, and concerts. While the old town of Santiago offers a traditional atmosphere with its winding streets and historic sites, the modern side can be seen around the university area and in art galleries. The Cidade da Cultura stands out as one of the most surprising examples of contemporary architecture in Galicia.
name: Cidade da Cultura de Galicia
address: Monte Gaiás, s/n, 15707 Santiago de Compostela, A Coruña, Spain

detail_description: Pr. da Quintana de Vivos, also known as Quintana Square, is a historic site located at the confluence of the south facade of the cathedral, Parra House, Convent of San Paio de Antealtares and Conga house. This 16th-century space features characteristic steps and was historically used for public events including vindictive gatherings, entertainment, and popular concerts.
name: Pr. da Quintana de Vivos
address: Santiago de Compostela, 15704 Santiago de Compostela, A Coruña, Spain

excerpt: Now a refined hotel, this historic convent sits near a Gothic cathedral, museum & notable monuments.
detail_description: Convento de San Francisco de Santiago, originally a 13th-century monastery for Franciscan friars, has been transformed into a refined hotel and restaurant. The historic building is located near a Gothic cathedral and notable monuments. The former convent now offers excellent facilities, delicious food with a special Pilgrim menu featuring typical monastery dishes, and top-notch service.
name: Convento de San Francisco de Santiago
address: Rúa do Campiño de San Francisco, 3, 15704 Santiago de Compostela, A Coruña, Spain

excerpt: Art, exhibits & artifacts related to the history of pilgrimages to Santiago de Compostela.
detail_description: The Museum of Pilgrimage, also known as Museo das Peregrinacions e de Santiago, is a captivating destination in the Praza das Praterias. It offers a deep dive into the history of pilgrimages to Santiago de Compostela. The museum showcases an array of art, exhibits, and artifacts related to the epic pilgrimage towards Santiago that draws thousands of people annually.
name: Museum of Pilgrimage
address: Praza das Praterías, 2, 15704 Santiago de Compostela, A Coruña, Spain

excerpt: Tranquil park with shaded walkways, gardens, views of nearby landmarks & ruins of an old cemetery.
detail_description: Parque de San Domingos de Bonaval is a serene and picturesque park surrounded by Gothic and Baroque architecture. The lush hydrangea gardens, shaded woods, and well-maintained landscapes make it an ideal spot for a leisurely stroll or a peaceful picnic. From the lawn above the old monastic cemetery, visitors can enjoy perfect views of the nearby cathedral towers to the west. Additionally, the park offers beautiful vistas of Santiago and features a water fountain dating back to 1747.
name: Parque de San Domingos de Bonaval
address: Costa de San Domingos, 3, 15703 Santiago de Compostela, A Coruña, Spain

detail_description: Fundación Eugenio Granell, also known as Pazo do Marqués de Bendaña, is a space dedicated to the surrealist painter from Coruna. Established in 1995, it houses a collection of Granell's works including oils, sculptures, drawings, and collages. The foundation also features pieces by other artists such as Miro, Lam, Caballero, Copley, and Duchamp.
name: Fundación Eugenio Granell / Pazo do Marqués de Bendaña
address: Praza do Toural, 8, 15705 Santiago de Compostela, A Coruña, Spain

detail_description: Located just a short walk from Plaza de las Praterias, you'll find the charming Plaza de Fonseca. This square is surrounded by cozy cafes and offers a delightful view of the Colexio de Fonseca with its magnificent Renaissance courtyard. Dating back to 1495, this was once the main site of the Santiago university, adding historical significance to its already picturesque setting.
name: Praza de Fonseca
address: Santiago de Compostela, A Coruña, Spain

excerpt: Monastery featuring a grand interior, religious art museum & facade with a carved stone altarpiece.
detail_description: Located in the heart of Santiago's old quarter, Mosteiro de San Martiño Pinario is a must-visit destination for history and art enthusiasts. The monastery boasts a grand interior and houses a religious art museum. As you explore the surrounding area, you'll encounter the magnificent facade of the convent, adorned with a carved stone altarpiece, as well as a stunning Baroque twin staircase nearby.
name: Mosteiro de San Martiño Pinario
address: Pl. de San Martiño, S/N, 15704 Santiago de Compostela, A Coruña, Spain

detail_description: Praza da Inmaculada is home to the baroque Casa do Cabildo, a stunning 3m-deep facade built in the 1750s. Located along the lower side of Praza das Praterias, this architectural gem is a must-see for visitors exploring the area.
name: Praza da Inmaculada
address: Santiago de Compostela, 15704 Santiago de Compostela, A Coruña, Spain

excerpt: Museum dedicated to Galician history & culture housed in a convent founded in the 13th century.
detail_description: The Museo del Pueblo Gallego is a captivating museum dedicated to the history and culture of Galicia, housed within a 13th-century convent complex. For a small fee, visitors can explore this impressive ethnographic museum featuring artifacts dating back to prehistoric times. The museum offers interactive exhibits and performances that bring Galician traditions to life. It provides an intriguing insight into the traditional culture of Galicia, showcasing trades, clothing, traditions, and the work of women.
name: Museum of the Galician People
address: Costa de San Domingos, 3, 15703 Santiago de Compostela, A Coruña, Spain

name: Parque infantil da Alameda de Santiago
address: Av. de Antonio Raimundo Ibáñez, 14, 15705 Santiago de Compostela, A Coruña, Spain

detail_description: The Camino de Finisterre offers a challenging yet rewarding journey with breathtaking landscapes that never fail to impress. Along the way, there are numerous establishments where travelers can refuel with a variety of local products. The path is not only a physical challenge but also an opportunity for inner discovery. Hostels such as Casa Loncho, Casa Pepa, Albergue O Logoso, and Albergue Bela Muxia provide hospitality along the route.
name: Camino de Finisterre
address: Rua Sarela de Abaixo, 53, 15898 Santiago de Compostela, A Coruña, Spain
